1
00:00:00,669 --> 00:00:03,070
Here’s the most common scenario.

2
00:00:03,070 --> 00:00:08,300
You see a trade setup, you decide it’s a
good one and you pull the trigger.

3
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:13,610
Then you place the stop loss, set the take
profit, and that’s it.

4
00:00:13,610 --> 00:00:18,030
Sometimes it hits your stop, sometimes prices
goes right to your target.

5
00:00:18,030 --> 00:00:22,680
But what about those times when price almost
hits your level?

6
00:00:22,680 --> 00:00:25,800
Do you know how to protect your trade?

7
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:27,630
What if it returns to your entry?

8
00:00:27,630 --> 00:00:29,789
Do you know what to do?

9
00:00:29,789 --> 00:00:34,250
What if it hits your stop loss in the first
place, and then starts to go in your initial

10
00:00:34,250 --> 00:00:35,640
direction?

11
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:40,960
And what if your take profit is too low and
you’re settling with a small gain?

12
00:00:40,960 --> 00:00:46,210
Taking profit is one of the most critical
aspects of a successful trading strategy.

13
00:00:46,210 --> 00:00:49,199
You want to minimize your risk and maximize
your profits.

14
00:00:49,199 --> 00:00:51,579
Today we’ll talk about this.

15
00:00:51,579 --> 00:00:56,890
So like, subscribe and stick around for the
full video.

16
00:00:56,890 --> 00:01:02,950
Setting single profit targets
Setting single profit targets can seem like

17
00:01:02,950 --> 00:01:08,290
a simple and straightforward strategy, but
it comes with several disadvantages that you

18
00:01:08,290 --> 00:01:09,830
should be aware of.

19
00:01:09,830 --> 00:01:15,540
First, consider the missed opportunities:
By setting a single profit target, you may

20
00:01:15,540 --> 00:01:19,850
miss out on potential profits as the market
moves in your favor.

21
00:01:19,850 --> 00:01:26,570
For example, if you set a profit target at
the price of $100 and it continues to rise

22
00:01:26,570 --> 00:01:31,120
after hitting that target, you would miss
out on the additional gains.

23
00:01:31,120 --> 00:01:35,830
Rigidity and lack of flexibility is another
disadvantage.

24
00:01:35,830 --> 00:01:40,990
Single profit targets can limit your ability
to adapt to market changes.

25
00:01:40,990 --> 00:01:46,650
If the market almost hits your target, then
moves in the other direction, you may be unable

26
00:01:46,650 --> 00:01:52,799
to take advantage of new opportunities or
adjust your strategy accordingly.

27
00:01:52,799 --> 00:01:57,960
Not to mention the psychological burden: You
may feel the pressure to reach that target

28
00:01:57,960 --> 00:02:01,090
and may be more likely to make impulsive decisions.

29
00:02:01,090 --> 00:02:07,420
It’s important to be aware of the disadvantages
of setting single profit targets and consider

30
00:02:07,420 --> 00:02:09,140
alternative approaches.

31
00:02:09,140 --> 00:02:13,930
The benefits of scaling out of positions (multiple
targets)

32
00:02:13,930 --> 00:02:21,160
A better strategy is to scale out of positions
and have multiple profit targets.

33
00:02:21,160 --> 00:02:27,580
Scaling out of positions refers to closing
partial positions at different levels of profit,

34
00:02:27,580 --> 00:02:32,770
rather than holding on to the entire position
until the target is hit.

35
00:02:32,770 --> 00:02:38,580
Let's say you buy a stock at $20 and set a
target profit of $30.

36
00:02:38,580 --> 00:02:44,010
Instead of holding on to the stock until it
reaches this price, you may choose to sell

37
00:02:44,010 --> 00:02:50,970
half of the position at $25 and the remaining
half at $30.

38
00:02:50,970 --> 00:02:53,140
This strategy has several benefits.

39
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:58,610
First, it reduces the risk of giving back
all of the profits if the market suddenly

40
00:02:58,610 --> 00:03:00,410
moves against you.

41
00:03:00,410 --> 00:03:04,510
By selling partial positions at different
levels of profit, you lock in profits and

42
00:03:04,510 --> 00:03:06,750
reduce your exposure to the market.

43
00:03:06,750 --> 00:03:12,290
Second, scaling out of positions allows you
to manage your emotions and avoid becoming

44
00:03:12,290 --> 00:03:14,840
too attached to a trade.

45
00:03:14,840 --> 00:03:20,049
Holding on to a position for too long can
create anxiety and fear, especially if the

46
00:03:20,049 --> 00:03:24,330
market moves against you, when you’ve already
been in profit.

47
00:03:24,330 --> 00:03:30,160
By selling partial positions, you can reduce
the emotional impact of a trade and make more

48
00:03:30,160 --> 00:03:32,239
rational decisions.

49
00:03:32,239 --> 00:03:38,240
You can also leave a portion of your trade
open even after you final target is reached.

50
00:03:38,240 --> 00:03:44,700
You bought at $50 and sets 2 profit targets:
$55 and $60.

51
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:52,290
You can sell 25% of your trade at the first
target, 50% at the second and final target,

52
00:03:52,290 --> 00:03:55,450
locking in profits and reducing your exposure.

53
00:03:55,450 --> 00:03:57,689
And you let the remaining size opened.

54
00:03:57,689 --> 00:04:02,500
Who know, maybe the market will move to $70,
$80.

55
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:05,730
This way, you have a chance to capture a much
bigger move.

56
00:04:05,730 --> 00:04:13,630
The benefits of trailing stop-loss orders
A trailing stop can be a powerful tool to

57
00:04:13,630 --> 00:04:18,919
ensure that you maximize your profits while
minimizing your risks.

58
00:04:18,919 --> 00:04:25,060
Suppose you bought a stock at $100 and set
a trailing stop at $10.

59
00:04:25,060 --> 00:04:31,900
If the stock price rises to $110, your stop
loss will adjust to breakeven, at $100.

60
00:04:31,900 --> 00:04:37,940
If the price continues to rise to $120, your
stop loss will continue to move up, always

61
00:04:37,940 --> 00:04:41,540
remaining $10 below the current price.

62
00:04:41,540 --> 00:04:46,580
The most obvious benefit of using a trailing
stop is that it allows you to maximize your

63
00:04:46,580 --> 00:04:47,610
profits.

64
00:04:47,610 --> 00:04:53,509
By continuously adjusting your stop loss as
the price moves in your favor, you can lock

65
00:04:53,509 --> 00:04:58,170
in profits while avoiding premature exits.

66
00:04:58,170 --> 00:05:04,100
This can be especially useful when the market
is trending in your direction.

67
00:05:04,100 --> 00:05:09,139
Another benefit of using a trailing stop is
that it helps you minimize your risk.

68
00:05:09,139 --> 00:05:14,840
As the price moves in your favor, your stop
loss moves with it, ensuring that you are

69
00:05:14,840 --> 00:05:17,700
protected in case the market turns against
you.

70
00:05:17,700 --> 00:05:23,150
This way, you can avoid losing money on a
trade that was in profit.

71
00:05:23,150 --> 00:05:29,340
A trailing stop is a dynamic exit point that
changes as the price changes.

72
00:05:29,340 --> 00:05:34,770
This allows you to stay in a trade for as
long as possible while still protecting your

73
00:05:34,770 --> 00:05:35,770
profits.

74
00:05:35,770 --> 00:05:40,870
You can choose a trailing stop based on a
percentage of the price or a set number of

75
00:05:40,870 --> 00:05:43,970
pips, depending on your personal preferences.

76
00:05:43,970 --> 00:05:50,870
Never use a dollar target as take profit
Here’s a common mistake.

77
00:05:50,870 --> 00:05:57,560
You see a trade opportunity, you enter, and
you set a money target of $100.

78
00:05:57,560 --> 00:06:03,600
When you see that you are 100$ in profit,
you exit, even though the price may have further

79
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:05,620
room to develop.

80
00:06:05,620 --> 00:06:11,340
While the idea of having a specific amount
of profit in mind can be motivating, it can

81
00:06:11,340 --> 00:06:14,889
also be an obstacle to your trading account
growth.

82
00:06:14,889 --> 00:06:19,380
There are several disadvantages when you set
money targets.

83
00:06:19,380 --> 00:06:24,139
First, a money target can cause you to make
irrational decisions.

84
00:06:24,139 --> 00:06:29,780
When you are so focused on reaching a specific
monetary goal, you will make impulsive trades

85
00:06:29,780 --> 00:06:35,850
or hold losing positions longer than they
should, which can lead to bigger losses.

86
00:06:35,850 --> 00:06:39,740
Second, money targets are not always realistic.

87
00:06:39,740 --> 00:06:45,340
You may set an overly optimistic target, which
can lead to disappointment and frustration

88
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:47,680
when the target is not met.

89
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:53,139
And on the other hand, setting a target that
is too conservative can result in missed opportunities

90
00:06:53,139 --> 00:06:54,430
for profits.

91
00:06:54,430 --> 00:07:00,180
So, instead, you should focus on developing
a comprehensive trading strategy that takes

92
00:07:00,180 --> 00:07:06,199
into account market conditions, volatility,
and other price action factors.

93
00:07:06,199 --> 00:07:13,090
Previous swing highs/lows
Scaling out of positions at previous swing

94
00:07:13,090 --> 00:07:20,259
highs or lows is probably the simplest strategy
if you are looking to manage risk and maximize

95
00:07:20,259 --> 00:07:21,259
profits.

96
00:07:21,259 --> 00:07:27,270
Basically, you take partial profits and minimize
the impact of potential market reversals.

97
00:07:27,270 --> 00:07:31,440
Let’s say you have a short position in a
downtrend.

98
00:07:31,440 --> 00:07:37,000
If the price reaches a new swing low, you
take some profits off the table and reduce

99
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:38,729
your exposure.

100
00:07:38,729 --> 00:07:42,449
At the same time you can move your stop to
breakeven.

101
00:07:42,449 --> 00:07:47,449
This can provide a safety cushion in the event
of a market downturn.

102
00:07:47,449 --> 00:07:53,229
You can use the swing high or low points to
re-evaluate your trading plan and make any

103
00:07:53,229 --> 00:07:54,949
necessary adjustments.

104
00:07:54,949 --> 00:08:02,091
For example, if price reaches a swing low
but then fails to break out to new lows, this

105
00:08:02,091 --> 00:08:07,290
may indicate a change in market sentiment
and you may want to consider exiting your

106
00:08:07,290 --> 00:08:16,110
position altogether or adjust your stop loss
levels even closer to the current price.

107
00:08:16,110 --> 00:08:18,919
Supply/demand

108
00:08:18,919 --> 00:08:23,400
Taking profits at supply and demand areas
is another strategy.

109
00:08:23,400 --> 00:08:28,560
The main idea behind this approach is to take
advantage of the natural forces of supply

110
00:08:28,560 --> 00:08:32,560
and demand that drive the price movement of
a market.

111
00:08:32,560 --> 00:08:38,590
For example, you bought at this demand level
and price has risen to a significant level

112
00:08:38,590 --> 00:08:39,590
of supply.

113
00:08:39,590 --> 00:08:42,740
Here you may choose to sell a part of your
position.

114
00:08:42,740 --> 00:08:49,090
This way, even if the price does eventually
fall, you will have already captured some

115
00:08:49,090 --> 00:08:52,560
gains and protected your capital.

116
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:58,260
Another benefit of scaling out of positions
at supply and demand areas is that it can

117
00:08:58,260 --> 00:09:01,880
increase the efficiency of your account balance.

118
00:09:01,880 --> 00:09:08,120
By closing partial positions at key levels,
you can free up capital that can then be used

119
00:09:08,120 --> 00:09:12,280
to enter new positions.

120
00:09:12,280 --> 00:09:17,930
ATR/ADR
Taking profits using average true range or

121
00:09:17,930 --> 00:09:21,630
average daily range (ATR) is another strategy.

122
00:09:21,630 --> 00:09:27,320
This technique involves monitoring the market’s
volatility, as measured by the average true

123
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:32,780
range, and using it to determine the best
time to take profits.

124
00:09:32,780 --> 00:09:38,550
Knowing the average daily range is extremely
useful since it allows you to estimate how

125
00:09:38,550 --> 00:09:41,860
much profit potential there is in the market.

126
00:09:41,860 --> 00:09:48,089
For example, if you are a Forex day trader,
there is no point looking for 100 pips of

127
00:09:48,089 --> 00:09:55,160
profit from a trade, if the average daily
range for that currency pair is only 60 pips.

128
00:09:55,160 --> 00:10:01,680
The ATR can be used in combination with other
take profit strategies to improve the accuracy

129
00:10:01,680 --> 00:10:03,380
of trade timing.

130
00:10:03,380 --> 00:10:10,640
For example, you may choose to take partial
profits when the ATR crosses above a certain

131
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:17,190
level, and price reaches a major support or
resistance level, or an area of supply and

132
00:10:17,190 --> 00:10:18,830
demand.

133
00:10:18,830 --> 00:10:22,110
Fibonacci extensions

134
00:10:22,110 --> 00:10:28,440
Taking profits using Fibonacci extensions
is my favorite take profit method.

135
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:34,240
Fibonacci extensions can be used to project
potential levels of price action beyond a

136
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:35,240
retracement.

137
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:39,130
In short, you get clear and objective exit
points.

138
00:10:39,130 --> 00:10:46,680
For example, if you buy a market in an uptrend,
you can use Fibonacci extensions to find potential

139
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:52,110
levels of resistance where you can scale out
of your position.

140
00:10:52,110 --> 00:10:58,130
If the price reaches the 100% extension level,
you may choose to sell a part of your position,

141
00:10:58,130 --> 00:10:59,519
locking in profits while reducing your risk
exposure.

142
00:10:59,519 --> 00:11:05,339
If price continues to move higher, you may
choose to sell more of your position at the

143
00:11:05,339 --> 00:11:10,200
161% extension level, and maybe move your
stop higher.

144
00:11:10,200 --> 00:11:16,750
By using these clear and objective exit points,
you avoid overstaying in a trade.

145
00:11:16,750 --> 00:11:25,550
VWAP or Bollinger Bands
Using VWAP bands or Bollinger Bands is another

146
00:11:25,550 --> 00:11:28,839
alternative to scale out your positions.

147
00:11:28,839 --> 00:11:35,670
The idea is simple: you will use these bands
to identify dynamic support and resistance

148
00:11:35,670 --> 00:11:36,970
levels.

149
00:11:36,970 --> 00:11:42,670
If price is approaching the upper VWAP band,
it may be a good time to scale out of a long

150
00:11:42,670 --> 00:11:45,780
position and take profits.

151
00:11:45,780 --> 00:11:51,620
This is because the price is likely to experience
some resistance at the upper band, which may

152
00:11:51,620 --> 00:11:53,589
cause it to retrace.

153
00:11:53,589 --> 00:11:59,560
Similarly, if price is approaching a lower
Bollinger band, it may be a good time to take

154
00:11:59,560 --> 00:12:01,940
profits on a short position.

155
00:12:01,940 --> 00:12:07,760
This is because the price is likely to experience
some support at the lower band, which may

156
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:11,300
cause it to bounce back up.

157
00:12:11,300 --> 00:12:15,190
Pivot Points

158
00:12:15,190 --> 00:12:19,959
Taking profits using pivot points is another
reliable method.

159
00:12:19,959 --> 00:12:25,760
Rather than relying on subjective interpretations
of price action, pivot points offer a systematic

160
00:12:25,760 --> 00:12:28,870
approach you can use to make decisions.

161
00:12:28,870 --> 00:12:34,520
This can help you avoid the biases and emotions
that can often lead to poor decision-making.

162
00:12:34,520 --> 00:12:42,260
For example, if price reaches a resistance
level marked by a pivot point, you may choose

163
00:12:42,260 --> 00:12:49,420
to take some profits at that level in anticipation
of a potential price decline.

164
00:12:49,420 --> 00:12:57,269
End of the day/week
The end of the day or the week can be an ideal

165
00:12:57,269 --> 00:13:03,330
time to scale out of positions because it
allows you to take a step back and evaluate

166
00:13:03,330 --> 00:13:07,970
your positions in the context of wider market
conditions.

167
00:13:07,970 --> 00:13:13,389
If you are a day trader, and your trade is
in profit at the end of the session, you might

168
00:13:13,389 --> 00:13:14,540
want to limit your risk.

169
00:13:14,540 --> 00:13:20,320
You don’t know how the market will react
at the open of the next session.

170
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:24,899
The same if you are a swing trader, and you
have a decent profit on your trade.

171
00:13:24,899 --> 00:13:30,550
Before Friday’s end of the session, you
may want to reduce your overall risk.

172
00:13:30,550 --> 00:13:33,139
You’ve seen those big weekend gaps.

173
00:13:33,139 --> 00:13:38,630
So, take some profits off the table and move
our stop to breakeven.

174
00:13:38,630 --> 00:13:43,579
Taking profits in a trending market versus
a ranging market

175
00:13:43,579 --> 00:13:50,300
Taking profits in a trending market versus
a ranging market requires different approaches

176
00:13:50,300 --> 00:13:55,450
as the market dynamics and price movements
can be vastly different.

177
00:13:55,450 --> 00:14:01,880
In a trending market, prices move in a sustained
direction, whereas in a ranging market, prices

178
00:14:01,880 --> 00:14:04,899
oscillate within a certain range.

179
00:14:04,899 --> 00:14:10,740
In a strong trending market, you can look
to take profits at key levels of resistance,

180
00:14:10,740 --> 00:14:16,990
or at Fibonacci extension levels, where the
trend strength appears to decrease.

181
00:14:16,990 --> 00:14:22,490
On the other hand, taking profits in a ranging
market can be more challenging, making it

182
00:14:22,490 --> 00:14:25,360
difficult to determine when to take profits.

183
00:14:25,360 --> 00:14:30,170
Pivots are good targets when market is stuck
in a range.

184
00:14:30,170 --> 00:14:36,440
VWAP bands or Bollinger Bands are also very
useful during these conditions.

185
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:41,420
You need to understand the market conditions
and use the appropriate tools and techniques

186
00:14:41,420 --> 00:14:44,670
to determine when to take profits.

187
00:14:44,670 --> 00:14:51,959
Now, your take profit will never be hit if
your stop loss is constantly being hunted

188
00:14:51,959 --> 00:14:55,120
by market makers and smart money.

189
00:14:55,120 --> 00:15:00,430
If you want to learn how to avoid stop loss
hunting and avoid market manipulation, you

190
00:15:00,430 --> 00:15:02,930
must watch this video.

191
00:15:02,930 --> 00:15:08,370
And check out our academy program, if you
want to further level up your trading.

192
00:15:08,370 --> 00:15:08,809
Until next time!

